04553nam a22007095i 9780271035949DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710359497 a10.1515/97802710359492doi  a(DE-B1597)584045  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aKDZ432b.G73 2008 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a344.701/82221 aGraubart, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLegalizing Transnational Activism :bThe Struggle to Gain Social Change from NAFTA's Citizen Petitions /cJonathan Graubart. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Transnational Activism, Soft Law, and NAFTA's Social Model -- t1 Legalizing Politics -- t2 Politicizing Law -- t3 The Rise and Decline of NAFTA's Labor Petitions -- t4 The Importance of Institutional Support: NAFTA's Environmental-Petition Mechanism -- tConclusion: Lessons Learned -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe integration of national economies through the ongoing process that has come to be known as globalization has stirred much controversy, including outright resistance by activists who are concerned about globalization's negative impact on a variety of human values, such as protection of the environment and decent working conditions for labor. The political activism and social movements that have given rise to protests-like the violent demonstrations in Seattle at the WTO meeting in 1999-have been the subject of study by scholars, but less well known is the role that some institutional mechanisms associated with international trade agreements have played in providing "political opportunity structures" for activists to use in promoting their causes and gaining more support for them. In this book, Jonathan Graubart draws our attention to the citizen-petition mechanisms that form part of the neoliberal package of reforms known as the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) implemented by Canada, Mexico, and the United States. He provides a comparative case study of the North American Agreement on Labor Cooperation (NAALC) and North American Agreement on Environmental Cooperation (NAAEC) and shows how they have functioned as avenues for activists to publicize their domestic grievances and bring more pressure on their governments to institute needed change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCitizen suits (Civil procedure)zNorth America. 0aEnvironmental lawzNorth America. 0aEnvironmental protectionzNorth AmericaxCitizen participation. 0aFree tradexSocial aspectszNorth America. 0aLabor laws and legislationzNorth America. 0aLabor movementxPolitical aspectszNorth America. 0aLabor unionsxLaw and legislationzNorth America. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271035949zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271035949423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271035949.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK